addProblem(12,29,`Sample mean λ̂=2.900 calls. Use 6+ for the upper tail.\nExpected: 6.6028, 19.1481, 27.7647, 26.8392, 19.4584, 11.2859, 8.9009.\n${chiLine('4.7179',5,'0.45127','.05','11.070','false')}`,`The emergency-call data are consistent with a Poisson distribution.`);
addProblem(12,30,`Sample mean λ̂=2.600 accidents. Use 5+ for the upper tail.\nExpected: 7.4274, 19.3111, 25.1045, 21.7572, 14.1422, 12.2577.\n${chiLine('5.0192',4,'0.28534','.05','9.488','false')}`,`The accident counts are consistent with a Poisson distribution.`);
addProblem(12,31,`H₀: scores follow N(83.1,10.43²); H₁: they do not.\nUsing eight equal-probability intervals, observed counts are 4,4,4,9,4,4,6,5 (E=5 each).\n${chiLine('4.4000',5,'0.49337','.01','15.086','false')}`,`Two parameters are estimated, so df=8−1−2=5. Normality is not rejected.`);
addProblem(12,32,`H₀: shelf life follows N(23.07,4.29²); H₁: it does not.\nUsing six equal-probability intervals, observed counts are 2,11,7,2,3,5 (E=5 each).\n${chiLine('12.4000',3,'0.006131','.05','7.815','true')}`,`With df=6−1−2=3, the sample is not consistent with the proposed normal distribution.`);
addProblem(12,33,`Sample mean=74.00; sample SD≈12.82. Using eight equal-probability intervals gives observed counts 6,5,5,3,5,4,8,4 (E=5 each).\n${chiLine('3.2000',5,'0.66918','.10','9.236','false')}`,`The normal model is not rejected.`);
addProblem(12,34,`Sample mean=440.42; sample SD=163.2129. Ten equal-probability normal intervals give observed counts 5,5,6,1,9,2,11,0,3,8 (E=5 each).\n${chiLine('23.2000',7,'0.001573','.05','14.067','true')}`,`The sample does not come from the fitted normal distribution at α=.05.`);
addProblem(12,35,`a. Mean=440.42; sample SD=163.2129.\nb. With ten equal-probability intervals, χ²=23.2000 and df=7.\nc. Critical χ².05,7=14.067; reject H₀.\nd. p=0.001573.`, `The two fitted parameters reduce the degrees of freedom to 10−1−2=7. The data are not consistent with a normal population.`);

// Chapter 13 problems: source tables were visually checked against the PDF,
// including observations that the original text parser dropped when a value
// appeared alone on a line. Every reported ANOVA component was recomputed.
addProblem(13,1,`Overall mean=25.000.\nANOVA: Between SS=24, df=2, MS=12; Error SS=364, df=30, MS=12.1333; Total SS=388, df=32.\nF=0.9890; F.05(2,30)=3.3158; p=0.38375. Do not reject H₀.`, `H₀: μManagement=μFinance=μAccounting. The ACT-score means do not differ significantly at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,2,`Overall mean=26.000.\nANOVA: Between SS=408, df=3, MS=136; Error SS=410, df=41, MS=10; Total SS=818, df=44.\nF=13.6000; F.05(3,41)=2.8327; p=0.00000266. Reject H₀.`, `The four major means are not all equal. The question says “three populations,” but its source table contains four majors, so the correct numerator df is 3.`);
addProblem(13,3,`Means: 80, 83, 84; overall mean=82.\nANOVA: Between SS=36, df=2, MS=18; Error SS=190, df=9, MS=21.1111; Total SS=226, df=11.\nF=0.8526; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.45804. Do not reject H₀.`, `The source has a fifth Store 1 observation of 80 on a separate line. With all 12 observations included, average sales do not differ significantly among stores.`);
addProblem(13,4,`Means: 80, 86, 88; overall mean=84.6667.\nANOVA: Between SS=173.3333, df=2, MS=86.6667; Error SS=1,586, df=12, MS=132.1667; Total SS=1,759.3333, df=14.\nF=0.6557; F.05(2,12)=3.8853; p=0.53670. Do not reject H₀.`, `Both the p-value and critical-value approaches show no significant difference among average heating bills.`);
addProblem(13,5,`Completed ANOVA table:\nBetween: SS=36, df=2, MS=18, F=3.0000.\nError: SS=240, df=40, MS=6.\nTotal: SS=276, df=42.\nF.05(2,40)=3.2317; p=0.06110. Do not reject H₀.`, `There are N=18+10+15=43 observations and k=3 treatments. Since F is below the 5% critical value, the treatment means are not significantly different.`);
addProblem(13,6,`Means: 36, 39, 31; overall mean=36.\nANOVA: Between SS=120, df=2, MS=60; Error SS=62, df=9, MS=6.8889; Total SS=182, df=11.\nF=8.7097; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.00786. Reject H₀.`, `The PDF contains five Treatment 2 values (including 38 and 40) and three Treatment 3 values. With the full source data, the population means differ significantly.`);
addProblem(13,7,`Completed ANOVA table:\nBetween: SS=36, df=2, MS=18, F=4.5000.\nError: SS=108, df=27, MS=4.\nTotal: SS=144, df=29.\nF.05(2,27)=3.3541; p=0.02057. Reject H₀.`, `N=30 and k=3. Both decision methods show a significant difference among treatment means.`);
addProblem(13,8,`Means: 41, 35, 38; overall mean=38.25.\nANOVA: Between SS=80.25, df=2, MS=40.125; Error SS=90, df=9, MS=10; Total SS=170.25, df=11.\nF=4.0125; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.05678. Do not reject H₀.`, `The source has five Treatment 1, four Treatment 2, and three Treatment 3 observations. The result is close, but not significant at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,9,`Overall mean=58 months.\nANOVA: Between SS=448, df=2, MS=224; Error SS=770, df=21, MS=36.6667; Total SS=1,218, df=23.\nF=6.1091; F.05(2,21)=3.4668; p=0.008107. Reject H₀.`, `H₀: all three printer-brand mean lifetimes are equal. The sample provides significant evidence that at least one differs.`);
addProblem(13,10,`Means: 30, 32, 34; overall mean=32.\nANOVA: Between SS=48, df=2, MS=24; Error SS=200, df=15, MS=13.3333; Total SS=248, df=17.\nF=1.8000; F.05(2,15)=3.6823; p=0.19922. Do not reject H₀.`, `There is no significant difference among the three population means at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,11,`Means: 75.8, 81.0, 88.0; overall mean=81.6.\nANOVA: Between SS=374.8, df=2, MS=187.4; Error SS=1,438.8, df=12, MS=119.9; Total SS=1,813.6, df=14.\nF=1.5630; F.05(2,12)=3.8853; p=0.24932. Do not reject H₀.`, `The instructor-group average scores are not significantly different.`);
