addProblem(13,16,`Means: 42, 49, 44; overall mean=45 mpg.\nANOVA: Between SS=390, df=2, MS=195; Error SS=700, df=42, MS=16.6667; Total SS=1,090, df=44.\nF=11.7000; F.05(2,42)=3.2199; p=0.0000914. Reject H₀.`, `The model mean gasoline consumptions are significantly different.`);
addProblem(13,17,`Means: 69, 84, 63; overall mean=72.\nANOVA: Between SS=936, df=2, MS=468; Error SS=396, df=9, MS=44; Total SS=1,332, df=11.\nF=10.6364; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.004260. Reject H₀.`, `At least one population mean differs at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,18,`Means: 177, 184, 164; overall mean=176.375.\nANOVA: Between SS=481.875, df=2, MS=240.9375; Error SS=382, df=5, MS=76.4; Total SS=863.875, df=7.\nF=3.1536; F.05(2,5)=5.7861; p=0.13003. Do not reject H₀.`, `The three production-method means do not differ significantly at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,19,`Means: Diet A=17, B=14, C=20; overall mean=17.\nANOVA: Between SS=108, df=2, MS=54; Error SS=404, df=15, MS=26.9333; Total SS=512, df=17.\nF=2.0050; F.05(2,15)=3.6823; p=0.16917. Do not reject H₀.`, `H₀: all diet mean weight losses are equal. The data do not establish a difference in effectiveness at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,21,`Randomized-block ANOVA:\nBoxes: SS=24,467.2, df=2, MS=12,233.6, F=48.3988, p=0.00003396.\nStores: SS=711.0667, df=4, MS=177.7667, F=0.7033.\nError: SS=2,022.1333, df=8, MS=252.7667; Total: SS=27,200.4, df=14.\nAt α=.01, reject H₀ for boxes. Means are 200.0, 189.6, 280.0. Fisher LSD=.01=33.739: Box 3 differs from Boxes 1 and 2; Boxes 1 and 2 do not differ.`, `Store is the blocking factor, so its variation is removed from error. Box 3 produces the largest mean sales.`);
addProblem(13,22,`H₀: all four treatment means are equal.\nTreatments: SS=3,596.4, df=3, MS=1,198.8, F=3.6000.\nBlocks: SS=5,040, df=6, MS=840.\nError: SS=5,994, df=18, MS=333.\nTotal: SS=14,630.4, df=27.\nF.01(3,18)=5.0919; p=0.03385. Do not reject H₀ at α=.01.`, `Although the p-value is below .05, the question specifies the stricter 1% level; therefore the treatment result is not significant.`);
addProblem(13,23,`Overall mean=37.75.\nANOVA: Between SS=162.25, df=3, MS=54.0833; Error SS=948, df=40, MS=23.7; Total SS=1,110.25, df=43.\nF=2.2820; F.05(3,40)=2.8387; p=0.09383. Do not reject H₀.`, `The four population means do not differ significantly at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,24,`a. Completely randomized: Brands SS=198, df=3, MS=66; Error SS=300, df=8, MS=37.5; Total SS=498, df=11. F=1.7600, p=0.23229; do not reject H₀.\nb. Randomized block: Brands SS=198, df=3, MS=66, F=7.6154, p=0.01808; Radios SS=248, df=2, MS=124, F=14.3077; Error SS=52, df=6, MS=8.6667; Total SS=498, df=11. Reject H₀ for brands at α=.05.`, `Accounting for radio-to-radio differences removes SS=248 from error, reduces MSE from 37.5 to 8.6667, and reveals a significant battery-brand effect that the completely randomized analysis misses.`);
addProblem(13,25,`Two-factor ANOVA (3 programs × 2 sexes, n=2/cell):\nProgram: SS=36,150, df=2, MS=18,075, F=12.7588, p=0.006899.\nSex: SS=16,133.3333, df=1, MS=16,133.3333, F=11.3882, p=0.01496.\nInteraction: SS=1,516.6667, df=2, MS=758.3333, F=0.5353, p=0.61106.\nError: SS=8,500, df=6, MS=1,416.6667; Total SS=62,300, df=11.`, `At α=.05, both program and sex have significant main effects, but their interaction does not. Program means are A=310, B=197.5, C=317.5; female mean=311.667 versus male=238.333. Programs A/C outperform B descriptively; a post-hoc test would be needed for formal pairwise claims.`);
addProblem(13,26,`Means: 92, 88, 86; overall mean=88.6667.\nANOVA: Between SS=74.6667, df=2, MS=37.3333; Error SS=170, df=9, MS=18.8889; Total SS=244.6667, df=11.\nF=1.9765; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.19428. Do not reject H₀.`, `There is no significant difference among the three class mean grades.`);
addProblem(13,27,`Means: 30, 34, 32; overall mean=32.\nANOVA: Between SS=32, df=2, MS=16; Error SS=88, df=9, MS=9.7778; Total SS=120, df=11.\nF=1.6364; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.24766. Do not reject H₀.`, `The mean hourly outputs of the three production processes are not significantly different.`);
addProblem(13,28,`Means: 39, 41, 43; overall mean=41.\nANOVA: Between SS=48, df=2, MS=24; Error SS=200, df=15, MS=13.3333; Total SS=248, df=17.\nF=1.8000; F.05(2,15)=3.6823; p=0.19922. Do not reject H₀.`, `Average income does not differ significantly among departments at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,29,`Means: 82, 86, 81; overall mean=83.\nANOVA: Between SS=70, df=2, MS=35; Error SS=62, df=12, MS=5.1667; Total SS=132, df=14.\nF=6.7742; F.05(2,12)=3.8853; p=0.01074. Reject H₀.`, `Average heating bills differ significantly among the three heating methods.`);
addProblem(13,30,`Means: Northern=81, Central=87, Southern=82; overall mean=83.\nANOVA: Between SS=90, df=2, MS=45; Error SS=100, df=12, MS=8.3333; Total SS=190, df=14.\nF=5.4000; F.01(2,12)=6.9266; p=0.02126. Do not reject H₀ at α=.01.`, `The source includes a sixth Southern score of 85. The result would be significant at 5%, but the question requires 1%, so the correct decision is not to reject.`);
addProblem(13,31,`Means: A=180, B=174, C=176; overall mean=177.\nANOVA: Between SS=84, df=2, MS=42; Error SS=242, df=9, MS=26.8889; Total SS=326, df=11.\nF=1.5620; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.26163. Do not reject H₀.`, `The page break contains additional A values 176 and 190 and a B value 172. Using all 12 source observations, average speeds do not differ significantly.`);
addProblem(13,32,`Between: SS=90, df=3, MS=30, F=5.0000.\nError: SS=120, df=20, MS=6.\nTotal: SS=210, df=23.\nF.01(3,20)=4.9382; p=0.009510. Reject H₀ at α=.01.\nNumber of groups=4; total observations=24.`, `The numerator df is k−1=3, and total N is error df+k=20+4=24.`);
addProblem(13,33,`Between: SS=126, df=7, MS=18, F=4.5000.\nError: SS=240, df=60, MS=4.\nTotal: SS=366, df=67.\nF.05(7,60)=2.1665; p=0.0004406. Reject H₀.`, `Eight groups give 7 treatment degrees of freedom; N=68 gives 60 error degrees of freedom.`);
addProblem(13,34,`Means: 8, 11, 8; overall mean=9.\nANOVA: Between SS=24, df=2, MS=12; Error SS=22, df=9, MS=2.4444; Total SS=46, df=11.\nF=4.9091; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.03618. Reject H₀.`, `Average daily sales differ significantly among the three stores.`);
addProblem(13,35,`Randomized-block ANOVA:\nAutomobiles: SS=10, df=1, MS=10, F=1.4286, p=0.29801.\nDrivers: SS=32, df=4, MS=8, F=1.1429.\nError: SS=28, df=4, MS=7; Total SS=70, df=9.\nF.05(1,4)=7.7086. Do not reject H₀.`, `After blocking on driver, the two automobile makes do not have significantly different mean miles per gallon.`);
addProblem(13,36,`Two-factor ANOVA (2×2, n=2/cell):\nFactor A: SS=8, df=1, MS=8, F=1.3333, p=0.3125.\nFactor B: SS=8, df=1, MS=8, F=1.3333, p=0.3125.\nA×B: SS=8, df=1, MS=8, F=1.3333, p=0.3125.\nError: SS=24, df=4, MS=6; Total SS=48, df=7. F.05(1,4)=7.7086.`, `Neither main effect nor the interaction effect is significant at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,37,`Between: SS=82.4, df=2, MS=41.2; Error: SS=158.4, df=27, MS=5.8667; Total: SS=240.8, df=29.\nF=7.0227; F.05(2,27)=3.3541; p=0.003502. Reject H₀.\nFisher LSD=.05=2.2226. Means: 24.8, 23.4, 27.4. Mean 3 differs from Means 1 and 2; Means 1 and 2 do not differ.`, `Protected Fisher comparisons are appropriate because the overall F test is significant.`);
addProblem(13,38,`Between: SS=390.58, df=2, MS=195.29; Error: SS=158.4, df=21, MS=7.5429; Total: SS=548.98, df=23.\nF=25.8907; F.05(2,21)=3.4668; p=0.00000215. Reject H₀.\nFisher LSD=.05=2.8558. Means: 17.000, 21.625, 26.875; every pair differs significantly.`, `There are N=24 observations, so each of the three equal-sized treatments has n=8.`);
addProblem(13,39,`Between: SS=216, df=2, MS=108; Error: SS=252, df=21, MS=12; Total: SS=468, df=23.\nF=9.0000; F.05(2,21)=3.4668; p=0.001504. Reject H₀.`, `The three population means are not all equal at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,40,`Means: City I=268, II=207, III=217; overall mean=234.9167.\nANOVA: Between SS=9,552.9167, df=2, MS=4,776.4583; Error SS=6,322, df=9, MS=702.4444; Total SS=15,874.9167, df=11.\nF=6.7998; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.01587. Reject H₀.`, `Average daily television time differs significantly among the cities.`);
addProblem(13,41,`Means: 37, 38, 33; overall mean=36.\nANOVA: Between SS=140, df=2, MS=70; Error SS=81, df=27, MS=3; Total SS=221, df=29.\nF=23.3333; F.05(2,27)=3.3541; p=0.00000130. Reject H₀.`, `Average mileage differs significantly among the tire brands.`);
addProblem(13,42,`Means: Store 1=45, Store 2=36, Store 3=33; overall mean=39.\nANOVA: Between SS=324, df=2, MS=162; Error SS=36, df=9, MS=4; Total SS=360, df=11.\nF=40.5000; F.05(2,9)=4.2565; p=0.00003162. Reject H₀.`, `Average sales differ significantly among the three stores.`);
addProblem(13,43,`Completed ANOVA table:\nBetween: SS=1,500, df=3, MS=500, F=5.0000.\nError: SS=4,000, df=40, MS=100.\nTotal: SS=5,500, df=43.`, `Four treatments with 11 units each give N=44, treatment df=3, error df=40, and total df=43.`);
addProblem(13,44,`Overall mean=14.\nANOVA: Between SS=31.5, df=2, MS=15.75; Error SS=12.5, df=6, MS=2.0833; Total SS=44, df=8.\nF=7.5600; F.05(2,6)=5.1433; p=0.02293. Reject H₀.`, `The three population means are not all equal at α=.05.`);
addProblem(13,45,`Using the printed MS Between=800 and Total SS=10,600:\nBetween: SS=3,200, df=4, MS=800, F=7.0270.\nError: SS=7,400, df=65, MS=113.8462.\nTotal: SS=10,600, df=69.`, `The source prints stray question marks immediately after “800” and “10600.” Those two numbers must be treated as provided values; otherwise the table is underdetermined. With k=5 and N=70, the remaining entries follow uniquely.`);
addProblem(13,46,`Means: Tennessee=14, Kentucky=18, Texas=17; overall mean=15.8.\nANOVA: Between SS=33.6, df=2, MS=16.8; Error SS=62, df=7, MS=8.8571; Total SS=95.6, df=9.\nF=1.8968; F.05(2,7)=4.7374; p=0.21967. Do not reject H₀.`, `The continued table contains Tennessee values 17, 10, and 18 plus Kentucky value 20. Using all 10 observations, average handgun sales do not differ significantly among states.`);
addProblem(13,47,`Overall mean salary=$180,000.\nANOVA (salary units in $1,000): Between SS=83,160, df=2, MS=41,580; Error SS=538, df=30, MS=17.9333; Total SS=83,698, df=32.\nF=2,318.5874; F.05(2,30)=3.3158; p≈1.32×10⁻³³. Reject H₀.`, `The mean annual salaries of the three specialties differ overwhelmingly at α=.05.`);

// Chapter 14 problems: simple-regression coefficients, sums of squares,
// t/F tests, confidence intervals, and prediction intervals were recomputed.
addProblem(14,2,`Using ŷ=1.04155+0.00990716x: SSR=6.19197, SSE=4.80803, df=(1,5).\na. F=6.4392; F.01(1,5)=16.2582; p=0.05205. Do not reject H₀.\nb. t=2.5376; t.005,5=4.0321; p=0.05205. Do not reject H₀.\nc. At x=800, ŷ=8.9673; 90% CI for mean price=(7.2357, 10.6988).\nd. 90% prediction interval for one book=(6.3400, 11.5946).`, `The F and two-sided t tests are equivalent in simple regression (F=t²). Neither is significant at α=.01. A prediction interval is wider because it includes individual-book variation.`);
addProblem(14,4,`Using ŷ=29.78571−0.728571x: SSR=37.15714, SSE=6.27143, df=(1,5).\na. F=29.6241; F.01(1,5)=16.2582; p=0.002842. Reject H₀.\nb. t=−5.4428; |t|>t.005,5=4.0321; p=0.002842. Reject H₀.`, `Price and units sold have a significant negative linear relationship at α=.01; the F and t decisions must agree.`);
addProblem(14,5,`a. n=10.\nb. t=−0.5556/0.1611=−3.4488, df=8, p≈0.00871; reject H₀.\nc. MSR=110; MSE=74/8=9.25; F=11.8919, p≈0.00871; reject H₀.\nd. R²=110/184=0.59783.`, `About 59.78% of the sample variation in Y is explained by its linear relationship with X. Small t/F differences arise only from rounded printed coefficients.`);
addProblem(14,6,`a. n=10.\nb. t=−0.511/0.304=−1.6809, df=8, p≈0.1313; do not reject H₀.\nc. MSE=67.989/8=8.49863; F=24.011/8.49863=2.8253, p≈0.1313; do not reject H₀.\nd. R²=24.011/(24.011+67.989)=0.26099.`, `Only about 26.10% of sample Y variation is explained by X, and the slope is not statistically significant at α=.05.`);
addProblem(14,7,`Regression Statistics: Multiple R=0.1347; R²=0.01814; Adjusted R²=−0.05739; Standard Error=3.3838; Observations=15.\nANOVA: Regression df=1, SS=2.7500, MS=2.7500, F=0.24017, Significance F=0.632; Residual df=13, SS=148.85, MS=11.45; Total df=14, SS=151.60.\nCoefficients: intercept t=3.8744; x t=0.4901.`, `R²=SSR/SST=2.75/151.60. The negative adjusted R² indicates that this one-predictor model performs worse than an intercept-only model after adjustment.`);
addProblem(14,8,`a. t=−1.106/0.261=−4.2375, df=13, p≈0.00097; reject H₀.\nb. MSE=82.936/13=6.37969; F=18.0360, p≈0.00095; reject H₀.\nc. R²=115.064/(115.064+82.936)=0.58113.`, `About 58.11% of sample Y variation is explained by X. The tiny t/F discrepancy is from rounded printed output; both tests show a significant negative relationship.`);
addProblem(14,9,`Multiple R=√0.5149=0.71757; Adjusted R²=0.4610.\nANOVA: Regression df=1, SS=514.9, MS=514.9, F=9.5529, Significance F=0.0129; Residual df=9, SS=485.1, MS=53.9; Total df=10, SS=1,000.\nIntercept≈111.8716; slope≈−2.16377.`, `The missing coefficients follow from coefficient=t×SE. Their last digits are approximate because the printed t statistics and standard errors are rounded.`);
addProblem(14,10,`a. t=−2.137/0.248=−8.6169, df=46, p<0.000000001; reject H₀.\nb. F=5048.818/(3132.661/46)=74.1369, p<0.000000001; reject H₀.\nc. R²=5048.818/8181.479=0.61710.\nd. r=−√R²=−0.78556.`, `About 61.71% of demand variation is explained by unit price. The relationship is strong, negative, and statistically significant.`);
addProblem(14,11,`a. n=41.\nb. t=0.029/0.021=1.3810, df=39, p≈0.1752; do not reject H₀.\nc. F=354.689/(7035.262/39)=1.9662, p≈0.1688; do not reject H₀.\nd. R²=0.04800.\ne. r=+0.21908.\nf. At X=50 ($50,000), ŷ=54.076+0.029(50)=55.526 thousand units=55,526 units.`, `Only about 4.80% of supply variation is explained by price. Rounded printed coefficients make t² and the SS-based F differ slightly, but both decisions are nonsignificant.`);
addProblem(14,12,`a. ŷ=2.86364+0.636364x.\nb. t=6.4807, df=2, p=0.02299; reject H₀ at α=.05.\nc. SSR=13.36364, SSE=0.63636; F=42.0000, p=0.02299; reject H₀.\nd. R²=0.95455.`, `The positive slope is significant, and about 95.45% of sample Y variation is explained by X.`);
addProblem(14,13,`a. ŷ=6.0000−0.8000x.\nb. t=−6.9282, df=3, p=0.006165; reject H₀.\nc. SSR=6.4, SSE=0.4; F=48.0000, p=0.006165; reject H₀.\nd. R²=0.94118.\ne. r=−0.97014.`, `X and Y have a strong, significant negative linear relationship.`);
addProblem(14,14,`a. ŷ=13.251+0.803x.\nb. t=0.803/0.385=2.0857, df=6, p≈0.0821; do not reject H₀.\nc. SSR=71.875−41.674=30.201; F=30.201/(41.674/6)=4.3482, p≈0.0821; do not reject H₀.\nd. R²=30.201/71.875=0.42019.`, `About 42.02% of sample variation is explained, but with only 8 observations the slope is not significant at α=.05.`);
addProblem(14,15,`a. ŷ=−9.462+0.769x.\nb. t=0.769/0.184=4.1793, df=6, p≈0.00582; reject H₀.\nc. MSE=138/6=23; F=400/23=17.3913, p≈0.00588; reject H₀.\nd. R²=400/(400+138)=0.74349.`, `About 74.35% of sample Y variation is explained by X, and the positive slope is significant.`);
addProblem(14,16,`a. The scatterplot would show a strong positive linear pattern.\nb. ŷ=−10.42105+0.789474x, where x is advertising in $10,000 and ŷ is sales in millions.\nc. At $400,000, x=40: ŷ=21.157895 million=$21,157,895.\nd. Each additional $10,000 of advertising is associated with about $0.78947 million higher predicted sales.\ne. R²=0.84586.\nf. F=32.9268, df=(1,6), p=0.001217; reject H₀.\ng. t=5.7382, df=6, p=0.001217; reject H₀.\nh. 95% CI for mean sales at x=40: (19.4579,22.8579) million.\ni. r=0.91971.`, `About 84.59% of sales variation is explained by advertising in this sample. The interval in part h is for average sales, not an individual-year prediction.`);
addProblem(14,17,`a. ŷ=8.3000−0.1500x.\nb. t=−15.0000, df=3, p=0.000643; reject H₀.\nc. SSR=22.5, SSE=0.3; F=225.0000, p=0.000643; reject H₀.\nd. R²=0.98684.\ne. r=−0.99340.`, `The data show an extremely strong and significant negative linear relationship.`);
addProblem(14,18,`a. ŷ=6.428+0.470x.\nb. t=0.470/0.035=13.4286, df=12, p≈1.37×10⁻⁸; reject H₀.\nc. SSE=1,021.429−958.584=62.845; F=958.584/(62.845/12)=183.0378, p≈1.26×10⁻⁸; reject H₀.\nd. R²=958.584/1,021.429=0.93847.\ne. r=+0.96875.`, `The positive relationship is extremely strong and significant. The small difference between t² and the SS-based F is caused by rounded printed coefficients.`);
addProblem(14,19,`a. ŷ=30.139−0.252x.\nb. t=−0.252/0.022=−11.4545, df=19, p<10⁻⁹; reject H₀.\nc. F=1,759.481/(259.186/19)=128.9813, p<10⁻⁹; reject H₀.\nd. R²=1,759.481/(1,759.481+259.186)=0.87161.\ne. r=−0.93360.`, `About 87.16% of sample Y variation is explained by X. Rounded output explains why the printed-coefficient t² is not exactly the SS-based F.`);
addProblem(14,20,`a. ŷ=75.06084−6.25364x; SSE=86.2615, SST=656.75, R²=0.86865.\nb. H₀:β₁=0; H₁:β₁≠0.\nc. t=−3.6369, df=2, p=0.06798; |t|<t.005,2=9.9248. Do not reject H₀ at α=.01.\nd. At x=10, ŷ=12.5244; 99% CI for mean monthly sales=(−33.1485,58.1974).\ne. 99% prediction interval for one month=(−67.0652,92.1140).`, `The fit is high descriptively, but n=4 leaves only 2 error degrees of freedom, so the relationship is not significant at 1%. Negative interval endpoints are mathematical outputs of the linear model and are not feasible sales counts.`);
addProblem(14,21,`a. Cups of coffee sold is Y; temperature is X.\nb. ŷ=605.7143−5.94286x.\nc. r=−0.95197.\nd. H₀:β₁=0; H₁:β₁≠0. t=−6.2180, df=4, p=0.003405; reject H₀.\ne. At 90°F, ŷ=70.857 cups (about 71).`, `Coffee sales have a strong, statistically significant negative linear relationship with temperature.`);
addProblem(14,22,`a. Hours of television is Y; age is X.\nb. ŷ=6.56433−0.124580x.\nc. H₀:β₁=0; H₁:β₁≠0. t=−12.0179, df=3, p=0.001240; reject H₀.\nd. R²=0.97965.`, `About 97.97% of the sample variation in television hours is explained by age through this fitted negative linear relationship.`);
addProblem(14,23,`a. ŷ=13.7500−1.1250x.\nb. t=−5.1962, df=5, p=0.003478; reject H₀.\nc. SSR=50.625, SSE=9.375; F=27.0000, p=0.003478; reject H₀.\nd. R²=0.84375.`, `The regression is significant, with 84.38% of sample Y variation explained by X.`);
addProblem(14,24,`a. Profit is Y; advertising cost is X.\nb. ŷ=210.06757+0.808108x.\nc. At x=$200, predicted profit=$371.69.\nd. t=6.4964, df=3, p=0.007406; reject H₀ at α=.05.\ne. R²=0.93363.`, `Advertising cost has a significant positive linear association with profit; about 93.36% of sample profit variation is explained.`);
addProblem(14,25,`a. Using the source value Y=.45, ŷ=4.34848+0.082576x and R²=0.007878.\nb. H₀:β₁=0; H₁:β₁≠0. t=0.15434, df=3, p=0.88714; do not reject H₀.\nc. At income x=20 ($20,000), ŷ=6.000; 95% CI for mean expenditure=(−0.1860,12.1860).\nd. 95% prediction interval for one customer=(−9.1526,21.1526).`, `The PDF clearly prints the first expenditure as .45; it also reproduces the given line exactly. The fitted relationship explains less than 1% of variation and is not significant. Negative endpoints are mathematical, not feasible expenditures.`);
addProblem(14,26,`a. ŷ=25.6000+5.2000x, with income in $1,000.\nb. At 6 years, ŷ=56.8 thousand=$56,800.\nc. R²=0.93889.\nd. t=6.7890, df=3, p=0.006533; reject H₀.\ne. F=46.0909, p=0.006533; reject H₀.`, `Years of college and annual income have a significant positive linear relationship in this sample.`);
addProblem(14,27,`a. ŷ=54.8341+7.53555x.\nb. R²=0.56784.\nc. t=1.6211, df=2, p=0.24645; do not reject H₀.\nd. F=2.6280, p=0.24645; do not reject H₀.`, `The fitted slope is positive, but four observations provide insufficient evidence of a linear age–book-expenditure relationship.`);
addProblem(14,28,`a. Annual income is Y; years of college is X.\nb. ŷ=21.6000+2.0000x (income in $1,000).\nc. At one year, ŷ=$23,600.\nd. t=1.5097, df=8, p=0.16956; do not reject H₀.\ne. R²=0.22173.\nf. r=+0.47088, a moderate positive sample association.`, `The sample correlation is positive, but the slope is not statistically significant at α=.05.`);
addProblem(14,29,`a. ŷ=16.20392+0.384812x (income in $1,000; x=age).\nb. At age 30, ŷ=27.7483 thousand=$27,748.\nc. R²=0.22657.\nd. t=1.2102, df=5, p=0.28027; do not reject H₀.\ne. F=1.4647, p=0.28027; do not reject H₀.`, `Age explains about 22.66% of sample income variation, but the fitted linear relationship is not significant.`);
addProblem(14,30,`a. ŷ=8.17092+9.45643x.\nb. R²=0.83005, indicating a strong fitted relationship.\nc. t=6.2508, df=8, p=0.0002455; reject H₀.\nd. F=39.0729, p=0.0002455; reject H₀.`, `GPA is a significant positive predictor of aptitude-test score in this sample, explaining about 83.01% of its variation.`);
addProblem(14,31,`a. Residual df=18, so n=20.\nb. t=0.12/0.045=2.6667, df=18, p≈0.01572; reject H₀.\nc. R²=1,400/(1,400+3,600)=0.2800.\nd. Advertising explains 28% of sample sales variation.\ne. At $4,000 advertising, X=4: ŷ=4.00+0.12(4)=4.48 million=$4,480,000.`, `Advertising and sales have a statistically significant positive relationship at α=.05, although most sales variation remains unexplained.`);
addProblem(14,32,`a. x̄=75/15=5; ȳ=135/15=9. b₁=−59/94=−0.627660; b₀=9−b₁(5)=12.13830. Thus ŷ=12.13830−0.627660x.\nb. SSR=100−62.9681=37.0319; R²=0.370319.\nc. F=37.0319/(62.9681/13)=7.6454; p=0.01607. Reject H₀ at α=.05.\nd. Setting ŷ=0 gives x=19.339 hundreds of dollars, or about $1,933.90.`, `The model explains about 37.03% of demand variation. The zero-demand price is an algebraic extrapolation and should not be treated as reliable if it lies outside the observed price range.`);
addProblem(14,33,`a. x̄=6, ȳ=9; b₁=37/84=0.440476; b₀=9−0.440476(6)=6.35714. Thus ŷ=6.35714+0.440476x.\nb. t=2.6388, df=5, p=0.04604; reject H₀ at α=.05.\nc. SSR=37²/84=16.29762; SSE=11.70238; F=6.9634, p=0.04604; reject H₀.\nd. R²=16.29762/28=0.58206.`, `The fitted positive linear relationship is significant at 5% and explains about 58.21% of sample Y variation.`);

// Chapter 15 problems: all coefficient tests use error df=n−k−1, and all
// overall tests compare MSR=SSR/k with MSE=SSE/(n−k−1).
addProblem(15,1,`a. ŷ=118.5059−0.0163X₁−1.5726X₂.\nb. Holding X₂ fixed, 100 additional company shares sold are associated with a $0.0163 lower predicted stock price. Holding X₁ fixed, one additional million shares of NYSE volume is associated with a $1.5726 lower price.\nc. X₁: p=0.6176, not significant. X₂: p=0.0018, significant at α=.05.\nd. For X₁=945 and X₂=16, ŷ=$77.9408.`, `The unit conversion matters: 94,500 shares becomes X₁=945 because X₁ is measured in hundreds.`);
addProblem(15,2,`a. R²=84/(84+112)=0.42857.\nb. For education, t=0.9210/0.190=4.8474, df=16, p=0.000178; reject H₀.\nc. F=(84/3)/(112/16)=4.0000, p=0.02658; reject H₀.\nd. Holding age and education fixed, a male (X₃=1) has predicted income $0.510 thousand ($510) lower than a female (X₃=0).`, `Gender is dummy-coded, so its coefficient is a group difference, not a one-unit continuous effect.`);
addProblem(15,3,`a. ŷ=4.0928+10.0230X₁+0.1020X₂−4.4811X₃.\nb. Holding GPA and age fixed, males are predicted to earn $4.4811 thousand less than females.\nc. R²=360.59/(360.59+23.91)=0.93782.\nd. X₁: t=6.0701, p=0.000907; significant.\ne. X₂: t=0.8327, p=0.4369; not significant.\nf. X₃: t=−3.1119, p=0.02080; significant.\ng. F=(360.59/3)/(23.91/6)=30.1623, p=0.000514; the model is significant.`, `All individual tests use df=10−3−1=6. The overall model can be significant even though age is not individually significant.`);
addProblem(15,4,`Regression df=384/48=8, so k=8 independent variables.\nSSE=704−384=320; error df=320/20=16.\nTotal df=8+16=24, so n=25.\nF=48/20=2.4000.`, `The table identities determine the missing counts: regression df equals the number of predictors, and total df=n−1.`);
addProblem(15,5,`a. ŷ=10−2X₁+6X₂−4X₃.\nb. R²=60/140=0.42857: 42.86% of sample Y variation is explained jointly.\nc. X₁: t=−2/1.5=−1.3333, df=16, p=0.2011; not significant.\nd. X₃: t=−4/1=−4.0000, p=0.001032; significant.\ne. SSE=80; F=(60/3)/(80/16)=4.0000, p=0.02658; the overall model is significant.`, `The total df of 19 gives n=20 and error df=16. Overall significance does not imply every predictor is individually significant.`);
addProblem(15,7,`a. ŷ=0.8051+0.4977X₁+0.4733X₂.\nb. At X₁=20 and X₂=10, ŷ=15.4921 automobiles.\nc. F=(40.700/2)/(1.016/4)=80.1181, p=0.000593; the model is significant.\nd. Price: t=0.4977/0.4617=1.0780, p=0.3417; not significant.\ne. Advertising spots: t=0.4733/0.0387=12.2300, p=0.000257; significant.\nf. R²=40.700/(40.700+1.016)=0.97564.`, `With n=7 and k=2, all tests use 4 error degrees of freedom.`);
addProblem(15,8,`a. ŷ=−11.340+0.798X₁+0.141X₂.\nb. Holding salespeople fixed, each additional $1,000 of advertising is associated with $0.798 million higher predicted sales. Holding advertising fixed, each additional salesperson is associated with $0.141 million higher sales.\nc. Advertising: t=2.4036, df=7, p=0.04721; significant at .05.\nd. Salespeople: t=0.5072, p=0.6276; not significant.\ne. X₁=50 and X₂=800 gives ŷ=141.36 million=$141,360,000.`, `Use X₁=50 because advertising is measured in thousands of dollars; X₂ is the literal salesperson count.`);
addProblem(15,9,`a. F=(822.088/2)/(736.012/7)=3.9093; p=0.07245. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.\nb. R²=822.088/(822.088+736.012)=0.52762.\nc. Adjusted R²=1−(1−R²)(9/7)=0.39266.\nd. n=2+7+1=10.`, `The unadjusted R² is 52.76%, but the overall model is not significant at 5%; adjusted R² reflects the small sample and two predictors.`);
addProblem(15,10,`a. ŷ=17.145−0.104X₁+1.376X₂.\nb. Holding spots fixed, a $1,000 higher unit price changes predicted sales by −0.104 computer; holding price fixed, one additional spot changes predicted sales by +1.376 computers.\nc. At X₁=2 and X₂=10, ŷ=30.697 computers.\nd. Price: t=−0.03169, df=9, p=0.9754; not significant.\ne. Advertising spots: t=5.5040, p=0.000378; significant.`, `The near-zero price t statistic comes from the very large coefficient standard error, not from the coefficient sign.`);
addProblem(15,11,`a. SSE=838.917−655.955=182.962; F=(655.955/2)/(182.962/9)=16.1334, p=0.001057. Reject H₀.\nb. R²=655.955/838.917=0.78191.\nc. Adjusted R²=1−(1−R²)(11/9)=0.73344.`, `The two predictors jointly explain about 78.19% of sample sales variation, and the overall model is significant.`);
addProblem(15,12,`a. ŷ=20.000+0.006X₁−0.70X₂.\nb. At X₁=10,000 and X₂=$50, ŷ=$45.\nc. Dow Jones: t=3.0000, df=27, p=0.005746; significant.\nd. Competitor price: t=−3.5000, p=0.001633; significant.`, `Both predictors are individually significant at α=.05 while holding the other predictor fixed.`);
addProblem(15,13,`a. With k=2 and error df=20, n=23.\nError MS=40 gives SSE=800. Since SST=800, SSR=0.\nb. F=(0/2)/40=0; p=1.000. Do not reject H₀.\nc. R²=0/800=0.`, `The printed table uniquely implies that the model explains none of the total variation.`);
addProblem(15,14,`a. t₁=−14.28/4.2=−3.4000; t₂=6.72/5.6=1.2000; t₃=15.68/2.8=5.6000 (df=12).\nb. X₁ (p=0.00527) and X₃ (p=0.000116) are significant; X₂ (p=0.2533) is not.\nc. X₂ is the candidate to drop, subject to theory and model hierarchy.\nd. R²=3285.4/3809.6=0.86240; adjusted R²=0.82800.\ne. SSE=524.2; F=(3285.4/3)/(524.2/12)=25.0698, p=0.0000187; the model is significant.`, `The three predictors jointly explain 86.24% of sample Y variation. Variable removal should not be based on a p-value alone when theory or hierarchy requires it.`);
addProblem(15,15,`a. ŷ=−15.0621+0.0972X₁+0.2484X₂.\nb. R²=562.363/(562.363+225.326)=0.71394.\nc. F=(562.363/2)/(225.326/9)=11.2310, p=0.003581; the model is significant.\nd. X₁: t=0.0972/0.054=1.8000, df=9, p=0.1054; not significant.\ne. n=2+9+1=12 supermarkets.`, `Food and nonfood sales jointly explain about 71.39% of profit variation, even though food sales is not individually significant at 5%.`);
addProblem(15,16,`a. Since Z=X², at X=5, Z=25 and ŷ=23.72+12.61(5)+0.798(25)=106.72.\nb. tX=12.61/4.85=2.6000; tZ=0.798/0.21=3.8000 (df=17).\nc. pX=0.01868 and pZ=0.001431; both coefficients are significant at α=.05.\nd. R²=520.2/(520.2+340.6)=0.60432; adjusted R²=0.55777.\ne. F=(520.2/2)/(340.6/17)=12.9821, p=0.000378; the quadratic model is significant.`, `X and X² jointly explain about 60.43% of sample Y variation. Because Z is a constructed squared term, interpret the curve as a whole rather than treating X and Z as unrelated business variables.`);
addProblem(15,17,`a. ŷ=0.0136+0.7992X₁+0.2280X₂−0.5796X₃.\nb. R²=45.9634/(45.9634+2.6218)=0.94604, a very strong fit.\nc. F=(45.9634/3)/(2.6218/11)=64.2812, p≈2.93×10⁻⁷; reject H₀.\nd. X₃: t=−0.5796/0.920=−0.6300, df=11, p=0.5416; not significant.`, `The overall model is highly significant, but additions to savings is not significant after controlling for income and family size.`);
addProblem(15,18,`a. R²=90/(90+100)=0.47368: the three predictors jointly explain 47.37% of sample Y variation.\nb. F=(90/3)/(100/16)=4.8000, df=(3,16), p=0.01432. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The overall relationship is significant even though the model leaves 52.63% of variation unexplained.`);
addProblem(15,19,`a. SSR=1,800−306=1,494; R²=1,494/1,800=0.8300.\nb. F=(1,494/8)/(306/60)=36.6176, df=(8,60), p≈2.61×10⁻²⁰. Reject H₀.`, `The eight predictors jointly explain 83% of sample variation, and the overall model is highly significant.`);
addProblem(15,20,`The source equation contains five predictors: ŷ=17+4X₁−3X₂+8X₃+5X₄+8X₅.\na. SSR=3,410−510=2,900; R²=2,900/3,410=0.85044.\nb. Error df=46−5−1=40; F=(2,900/5)/(510/40)=45.4902, p≈1.83×10⁻¹⁵. Reject H₀.`, `The five predictors jointly explain about 85.04% of sample Y variation, and the overall regression is significant.`);
addProblem(15,21,`a. ŷ=1.0211−0.1524Price+0.8849ADV−0.1463Lines.\nb. Price=30, ADV=40, Lines=10 gives ŷ=30.3821 units of $10,000=$303,821.\nc. R²=2708.61/(2708.61+2840.51)=0.48812.\nd. Price: t=−1.0801, df=14, p=0.2984; not significant.\ne. Lines: t=−0.0954, p=0.9254; not significant.\nf. F=(2708.61/3)/(2840.51/14)=4.4500, p=0.02147; the model is significant.\ng. Holding ADV and Lines fixed, each $100 higher price is associated with $1,524 lower predicted sales.\nh. n=3+14+1=18.`, `The model is jointly significant even though price and product lines are not individually significant; advertising supplies most of the evidence.`);
addProblem(15,22,`a. At X₁=40 and X₂=30, ŷ=40+8(40)+6(30)=540 million=$540,000,000.\nb. Advertising: t=8/2.5=3.2000, df=7, p=0.01507; significant.\nc. Salespeople: t=6/3=2.0000, p=0.08562; not significant.`, `The sample has n=10 and k=2, so coefficient tests use 7 error degrees of freedom.`);
addProblem(15,23,`a. For cans, PRICE=1.25, COMPRICE=1.50, ADV=200, CONTAIN=1: ŷ=322.849 units of $10,000=$3,228,490.\nb. PRICE: t=−2.7989, df=20, p=0.01108; significant.\nc. ADV: t=1.0870, p=0.2900; not significant.\nd. CONTAIN: t=−1.0475, p=0.3074; not significant.\ne. COMPRICE: t=1.3847, p=0.1814; not significant.`, `Advertising is measured in $1,000s, so $200,000 means ADV=200. Container is a dummy coefficient comparing cans with bottles while holding other predictors fixed.`);
addProblem(15,24,`a. R²=283,940.60/(283,940.60+621,735.14)=0.31351.\nb. F=(283,940.60/4)/(621,735.14/18)=2.0551, p=0.12940. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.\nc. n=4+18+1=23.`, `The four predictors explain about 31.35% of sample sales variation, but the overall model is not statistically significant.`);
addProblem(15,25,`a. X₃ is a dummy variable. Holding competitor sales and nearby population fixed, using any advertising is associated with $18,000 higher predicted sales than using none.\nb. X₁=3, X₂=10, and X₃=1 (advertising was used): ŷ=10−4(3)+7(10)+18(1)=86 thousand=$86,000.`, `Six radio advertisements still produces X₃=1, not 6; the model records whether advertising was used, not the number of ads.`);
addProblem(15,26,`a. ŷ=15,232.5+2,178.4X₁+7.8X₂+2,675.2X₃+1,157.8X₄.\nb. Holding other variables fixed, one additional room adds $2,178.40 to predicted value.\nc. A house with a garage (X₄=1) is predicted to be worth $1,157.80 more than one without.\nd. Regression df=4; error df=25.\ne. H₀:β₁=β₂=β₃=β₄=0. F=51,060.72/8,235.60=6.2000, p=0.001311; reject H₀.\nf. H₀:β₁=0. t=2,178.4/778.0=2.8000, df=25, p=0.009710; reject H₀.\ng. R²=204,242.88/(204,242.88+205,890)=0.49799.\nh. For 9 rooms, lot 7,500, 2 baths, and a garage (X₄=1), ŷ=$99,846.30.`, `Even if the house has two garage spaces, X₄ is only a presence dummy and must be entered as 1, not 2.`);
addProblem(15,27,`a. ŷ=450.08+49.92X₁+10.12X₂−0.60X₃.\nb. Holding other variables fixed: each family member adds $49.92; each meal out adds $10.12; having a member on a diet changes predicted food spending by −$0.60.\nc. With df=21 and α=.01: t₁=5.2000 (p=0.0000374), significant; t₂=4.6000 (p=0.000155), significant; t₃=−0.0500 (p=0.9606), not significant.\nd. Regression df=3; error df=21.\ne. F=1,026.13/95.90=10.7000, p=0.000178; the overall model is significant at .01.\nf. R²=3,078.39/(3,078.39+2,013.90)=0.60452.\ng. For X₁=4, X₂=3, X₃=0, ŷ=$680.12.`, `The diet dummy has essentially no estimated effect after controlling for family size and meals outside.`);
addProblem(15,28,`a. Holding competitors and nearby population fixed, having a drive-up window (X₃=1) adds $15,000 to predicted sales relative to no drive-up window.\nb. X₁=2, X₂=10, X₃=1: ŷ=18−2(2)+7(10)+15=$99,000.\nc. With X₃=0: ŷ=18−2(2)+7(10)=$84,000.`, `The difference between parts b and c is exactly the dummy coefficient: $15,000.`);
addProblem(15,29,`X₁=5, X₂=20, and X₃=1 because radio advertising was used.\nŶ=50−3(5)+20(20)+10(1)=445 thousand=$445,000.`, `Nine advertisements do not mean X₃=9; X₃ is a yes/no dummy.`);
addProblem(15,30,`a. X₁=9, X₂=30, X₃=0: Ŷ=40−3(9)+12(30)=373 thousand=$373,000.\nb. Radio advertising was used, so X₃=1: Ŷ=383 thousand=$383,000.`, `The dummy records whether advertising ran. Ten ads still enter the model as X₃=1, making the predicted difference exactly $10,000.`);

// Chapter 16 problems: quadratic terms, nested-model partial F tests, dummy
// coefficients, and completed ANOVA tables were checked against the PDF.
addProblem(16,1,`n=21, k=4, R²=.80, and S=√MSE=5.\nRegression: df=4, SS=1,600, MS=400, F=16.0000.\nError: df=16, SS=400, MS=25.\nTotal: df=20, SS=2,000.`, `MSE=S²=25, so SSE=25(16)=400. Since R²=1−SSE/SST=.80, SST=2,000 and SSR=1,600.`);
addProblem(16,2,`a. Linear model ŷ=2.7857+0.4643x: R²=.2596, F=2.1037, p=.1971. It is not significant at α=.05 and is inadequate.\nb. Quadratic model ŷ=−2.8393+3.8393x−0.375x²: R²=.9370, adjusted R²=.9118, F=37.1951, p=.0010. Both x (p=.0005) and x² (p=.0007) are significant; this model is adequate and much better.\nc. At x=4, ŷ=−2.8393+3.8393(4)−0.375(16)=6.5179.`, `The curved relationship is missed by a straight line. Significance and adjusted R² both favor the quadratic specification.`);
addProblem(16,3,`a. Linear model ŷ=3.3043+0.2609x: R²=.0932, F=.4110, p=.5564; inadequate at α=.05.\nb. Quadratic model ŷ=−2.6808+3.6803x−0.3133x²: R²=.9041, adjusted R²=.8401, F=14.1376, p=.0297. Both x (p=.0132) and x² (p=.0151) are significant; adequate at .05.\nc. At x=5, ŷ=−2.6808+3.6803(5)−0.3133(25)=7.8882.`, `The data rise and then fall, so the quadratic model captures structure the linear model cannot.`);
addProblem(16,4,`The model is ŷ=60+200x−6x², so k=2.\na. R²=600/(600+400)=0.6000.\nb. F=(600/2)/(400/20)=15.0000, df=(2,20), p=0.000105. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The two regression terms jointly explain 60% of sample variation and the quadratic relationship is significant.`);
addProblem(16,5,`H₀:β₂=0 given X₁; H₁:β₂≠0.\nPartial F=[(39.535−1.015)/1]/[1.015/(7−2−1)]=151.8030.\ndf=(1,4), p=0.000249; F.05(1,4)=7.7086. Reject H₀.`, `X₂ produces a very large reduction in SSE and contributes significantly after X₁ is already in the model.`);
addProblem(16,6,`a. The scatterplot rises at an increasing rate, showing strong upward curvature.\nb. Regressing Y on X² gives ŷ=−0.495935+0.101156X².`, `The specified model is Y=β₀+β₁X²+ε, not a full quadratic with a separate X term. The fitted R² is about 0.9202.`);
addProblem(16,7,`a. The scatterplot is increasing and visibly curved rather than linear.\nb. For Y=β₀+β₁X²+ε, the estimate is ŷ=1.25319+0.130928X².`, `Treat X² as the single transformed predictor. The fitted R² is about 0.9628.`);
addProblem(16,8,`Regression Statistics: Multiple R=0.91787; R²=0.84248; Adjusted R²=0.80048; Standard Error=72.6093; Observations=20.\nANOVA: Regression df=4, SS=422,975.2376, MS=105,743.8094, F=20.0572; Residual df=15, SS≈79,081.6567, MS≈5,272.1104; Total df=19, SS≈502,056.8943.\nt statistics: intercept −2.0302; X₁ 5.8405; X₂ 2.9231; X₃ 5.3276; X₄ −0.0050.\nAt 95% confidence, X₁ (p=.0000), X₂ (.0101), and X₃ (.0001) are significant; X₄ (.9961) is not.`, `The SS values derived from the printed standard error are approximate because 72.6093 is rounded. The variable decisions use the reported p-values.`);
addProblem(16,9,`n=20 and k=5.\nRegression: df=5, SS=570, MS=114, F=3.8000.\nError: df=14, SS=420, MS=30.\nTotal: df=19, SS=990.`, `Error SS equals MSE×df=30(14)=420; regression SS is the remaining 570.`);
addProblem(16,11,`a. H₀:β₃=β₄=β₅=0; H₁: at least one added coefficient is nonzero.\nb. Full model k=5, so error df=25−5−1=19. Partial F=[(725−520)/3]/(520/19)=2.4968, df=(3,19), p=0.09075. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The three added variables do not jointly reduce SSE enough to justify their addition at the 5% level.`);
addProblem(16,12,`a. Regression MS=80 with k=3 gives SSR=240; R²=240/(240+320)=0.42857.\nb. β₁: t=15/3=5.0000, df=16, p≈0.000128; significant.\nc. β₂: t=8/5=1.6000, p≈0.1292; not significant.\nd. β₃: t=−18/10=−1.8000, p≈0.0907; not significant.\ne. MSE=320/16=20; F=80/20=4.0000, p=0.02658; the overall model is significant.`, `An overall significant model may contain predictors that are not individually significant after controlling for the others.`);
addProblem(16,13,`Regression MS=125 with k=4 gives SSR=500; SST=760 gives SSE=260 and MSE=10 (df=26).\na. R²=500/760=0.65789.\nb. β₁: t=12/8=1.5000, p≈0.1456; not significant.\nc. β₄: t=16/2=8.0000, p<10⁻⁷; significant.\nd. F=125/10=12.5000, p=0.00000840; the overall model is significant.`, `The four predictors jointly explain about 65.79% of sample variation; X₄ is strongly significant while X₁ is not.`);
addProblem(16,14,`H₀:β₂=0 given X₁.\nPartial F=[(400−320)/1]/[320/(20−2−1)]=4.2500, df=(1,17), p=0.05488. F.05(1,17)=4.4513. Do not reject H₀.`, `The result is close but does not reach the specified 5% level, so X₂ is not shown to add significant explanatory power.`);
addProblem(16,15,`Partial F=[(50−40)/1]/[40/(30−2−1)]=6.7500, df=(1,27), p=0.01500. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `Adding X₂ significantly reduces SSE after X₁ is already in the model.`);
addProblem(16,16,`Partial F=[(495−396)/1]/[396/(33−2−1)]=7.5000, df=(1,30), p=0.01028. Reject H₀.`, `Competitor price contributes significantly after the company's own price is controlled.`);
addProblem(16,17,`The model is ŷ=120−0.03X₁+0.7X₂; n=15, k=2, df=12.\na. Price: t=−0.03/0.01=−3.0000, p≈0.0111; significant at α=.05.\nb. Promotion: t=0.7/0.1=7.0000, p≈0.000014; significant.`, `The promotion coefficient is a dummy-group effect: promotion predicts 0.7 more units sold, holding price fixed.`);
addProblem(16,18,`The model is ŷ=5,000+1.2X₁+0.9X₂; n=20, k=2, df=17.\na. Gender: t=0.9/0.1=9.0000, p<10⁻⁷; significant. Holding age fixed, females are predicted to earn 0.9 units more than males.\nb. R²=1,500/(1,500+500)=0.7500.`, `Because X₂ is coded 1 for female and 0 for male, the coefficient compares females with the male reference group.`);
addProblem(16,19,`R²=.80 and SSR=4,280 imply SST=5,350 and SSE=1,070.\nRegression: df=8, SS=4,280, MS=535, F=23.5000.\nError: df=47, SS=1,070, MS=22.7660.\nTotal: df=55, SS=5,350.\nF.05(8,47)=2.1427; p≈5.47×10⁻¹⁴. Reject H₀.`, `The eight-predictor model is highly significant and explains 80% of sample variation.`);
addProblem(16,20,`n=18, k=4, error df=13. Standard Error²=MSE=4.8²=23.04.\nError: df=13, SS=299.52, MS=23.04.\nSince R²=.36, SST=299.52/.64=468 and SSR=168.48.\nRegression: df=4, SS=168.48, MS=42.12, F=1.8281.`, `The supplied Multiple R=.60 is consistent with R²=.36. The overall model is not significant at 5% (p≈.1836), although the question only asks to fill the table.`);
addProblem(16,21,`a. Advertising: t=3.60/1.20=3.0000, df=7, p≈0.01994; significant at α=.05.\nb. With X₁=20 and X₂=300, ŷ=50+3.6(20)+0.2(300)=182 million=$182,000,000.`, `Advertising is measured in thousands, so $20,000 enters as 20; the salesperson count enters as 300.`);
addProblem(16,22,`R²=.80 and SSR=680 imply SST=850 and SSE=170.\nRegression: df=4, SS=680, MS=170, F=40.0000.\nError: df=40, SS=170, MS=4.25.\nTotal: df=44, SS=850.\np≈1.78×10⁻¹³; reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The four-predictor model is highly significant and explains 80% of sample variation.`);
addProblem(16,23,`H₀:β₃=β₄=0 given X₁ and X₂. The full model has k=4 and error df=45−4−1=40.\nPartial F=[(49−40)/2]/(40/40)=4.5000, df=(2,40), p=0.01727. Reject H₀.`, `The two added variables jointly contribute significantly at 95% confidence.`);
addProblem(16,24,`a. n=4+35+1=40.\nb. R²=27,641,631.121/(27,641,631.121+42,277,876.624)=0.39534.\nc-d. With df=35: Price t=−2.5411, p=0.01564; Competitor Price t=3.0569, p=0.004265; Advertising t=2.7342, p=0.009745; Type t=1.5206, p=0.13733.\ne. Price, Competitor Price, and Advertising are significant at .05; Type is not.\nf. F=6,910,407.780/1,207,939.332=5.7208, p=0.001189; the overall model is significant.`, `The type dummy is not individually significant after the other three predictors are controlled, even though the model as a whole is significant.`);
addProblem(16,25,`The full model has k=3 and error df=34−3−1=30.\nPartial F=[(300−250)/1]/(250/30)=6.0000, df=(1,30), p=0.02036. Reject H₀.`, `The third independent variable contributes significantly at 95% confidence.`);
addProblem(16,26,`The full model has k=7 and error df=48−7−1=40; q=2 added variables.\nPartial F=[(438−375)/2]/(375/40)=3.3600, df=(2,40), p=0.04479. Reject H₀.`, `The two added variables jointly contribute significantly, narrowly, at the 5% level.`);
addProblem(16,27,`R²=.60 and SSR=4,800 imply SST=8,000 and SSE=3,200.\nRegression: df=4, SS=4,800, MS=1,200, F=11.2500.\nError: df=30, SS=3,200, MS=106.6667.\nTotal: df=34, SS=8,000.\np=0.00001074; reject H₀.`, `The four-predictor model is significant and explains 60% of sample variation.`);
addProblem(16,28,`a. Overall F=328.56 with p<.0001; reject H₀. Sales is significantly related to at least one of advertising, price, or time.\nb. Advertising: t=.33, p=.7450, not significant. Price: t=2.78, p=.0112, significant. Time: t=6.05, p<.0001, significant.\nc. R²=.7744: the three predictors jointly explain 77.44% of the sample variation in company sales; 22.56% remains in residuals.`, `Use the overall F for joint model significance and each coefficient p-value for conditional individual significance.`);
addProblem(16,29,`a. December advertising is 28 units of $10,000. January 2010: 28(1.05)=29.4 units=$294,000. February: 29.4(1.05)=30.87 units=$308,700.\nb. With time 13 and 14:\nJanuary ŷ=13.01+0.31(29.4)+1.39(13)=40.194 units of $100,000=$4,019,400.\nFebruary ŷ=13.01+0.31(30.87)+1.39(14)=42.0397 units=$4,203,970.`, `The 5% increase compounds from January to February, and the time index continues after December as 13 and 14.`);

// Chapter 17 problems: moving-average, exponential-smoothing, trend, and
// multiplicative seasonal-decomposition calculations were independently
// recomputed from the source tables. Initial exponential forecasts equal the
// first actual value; MSE excludes the initialization period.
addProblem(17,1,`a. The least-squares trend is Tₜ=16+2t.\nb. At t=17, T₁₇=16+2(17)=50.`, `The observations increase by exactly 2 each period, so every point lies on the fitted trend.`);
addProblem(17,3,`Weights from oldest to newest are 2, 4, 6.\nApril=50.1667; May=56.5000; June=67.0000; July=78.5000.`, `For July, [2(60)+4(75)+6(87)]/12=78.5. The largest weight belongs to June, the most recent actual value.`);
addProblem(17,4,`Weights from oldest to newest are 3, 4, 5.\nApril=83.9167; May=87.2500; June=91.3333; July=95.0000.`, `For July, [3(90)+4(95)+5(98)]/12=95. The weights must be aligned by recency, not by the order in which they are printed.`);
addProblem(17,6,`With α=.3 and FJan=18:\nFFeb=18.000; FMar=20.100; FApr=23.070; FMay=28.149.`, `Each next-period forecast is Fₜ₊₁=.3Aₜ+.7Fₜ. Thus the April actual value of 40 produces the May forecast of 28.149.`);
addProblem(17,7,`a. α=.3: FFeb=18, FMar=20.1, FApr=23.07, FMay=28.149; MSE=144.5450.\nb. α=.1: FFeb=18, FMar=18.7, FApr=19.83, FMay=21.847; MSE=194.5063.\nc. α=.3 is better because it has the smaller MSE.`, `MSE uses the three forecast errors for February through April; May has no actual value and is therefore not included in the accuracy calculation.`);
addProblem(17,8,`Forecast errors A−F for observations 2–6 are −5, −4, 8, −6, 10.\nMAE=(5+4+8+6+10)/5=6.6.\nMSE=(25+16+64+36+100)/5=48.2.`, `Observation 1 has no forecast, so it is excluded from both denominators.`);
addProblem(17,9,`Errors for periods 2–6 are 3, −6, 2, 6, 10.\na. MAE=27/5=5.4.\nb. MSE=185/5=37.0.`, `The supplied forecasts are the naïve forecasts, but accuracy is computed in the usual way from the five available forecast errors.`);
addProblem(17,10,`Naïve forecasts for periods 2–6 are 12, 14, 10, 16, 29.\na. MAE=32/5=6.4.\nb. MSE=274/5=54.8.\nc. Forecast for period 7=22.`, `A naïve forecast is simply the most recent actual value. The period-7 forecast therefore equals the period-6 value.`);
addProblem(17,11,`Quarter averages are 180, 109, 280, and 231; the grand average is 200.\na. Seasonal indexes: Q1=.900; Q2=.545; Q3=1.400; Q4=1.155.\nb. For 2010 Q1, t=13 and trend=174+4(13)=226. Forecast=226(.900)=203.4 million.`, `The four multiplicative seasonal indexes sum to 4.0. The trend forecast must be multiplied by the Q1 index.`);
addProblem(17,12,`Quarter averages are 130, 276, 281, and 193; grand average=220.\na. Seasonal indexes: Q1=.590909; Q2=1.254545; Q3=1.277273; Q4=.877273.\nb. Trend-only forecast at t=13: 185.86+5.25(13)=254.11 million.\nc. Trend-and-seasonal forecast: 254.11(.590909)=150.1559 million.`, `The seasonal indexes sum to 4. Multiplying by the below-average Q1 index lowers the trend-only forecast.`);
addProblem(17,13,`Quarter averages are 24, 18, 38, and 12; grand average=23.\na. Seasonal indexes: Q1=1.043478; Q2=.782609; Q3=1.652174; Q4=.521739.\nb. Trend-only forecast at t=13: 20.82+.336(13)=25.188 million.\nc. Trend-and-seasonal forecast: 25.188(1.043478)=26.2831 million.`, `The four indexes sum to 4.0; Q1 is slightly above an average quarter.`);
addProblem(17,14,`a. The least-squares trend is Tₜ=12+1.464286t.\nb. T₁₀=12+1.464286(10)=26.6429 million.`, `The slope is Σ(t−t̄)(Y−Ȳ)/Σ(t−t̄)²=41/28=1.464286.`);
addProblem(17,15,`a. The least-squares trend is Tₜ=6.633333+.342857t, in thousands of students.\nb. T₁₀=10.0619 thousand students (about 10,062).`, `The fitted line summarizes the long-run direction even though enrollment drops in year 6.`);
addProblem(17,16,`a. Four-week moving-average forecasts: W5=17.00, W6=18.00, W7=19.00, W8=19.00, W9=20.00, W10=19.00, W11=19.25.\nb. MSE for weeks 5–10=7.6667.\nc. With α=.3: F2=15, F3=15.3, F4=16.41, F5=16.887, F6=17.5209, F7=18.26463, F8=18.485241, F9=19.539669, F10=18.177768.\nd. Exponential-smoothing forecast for week 11=19.024438 thousand.`, `The moving-average MSE uses only weeks 5–10, where forecasts and actuals both exist. The week-11 value is a forecast and is not part of that MSE.`);
addProblem(17,17,`a. Centered three-month averages (months 2–5): 5, 4, 7, 9 thousand.\nb. MSE=[(3−5)²+(4−4)²+(5−7)²+(12−9)²]/4=4.25.\nc. With α=.2: F2=8, F3=7, F4=6.4, F5=6.12, F6=7.296.\nd. Forecast for month 7=7.8368 thousand.`, `A centered moving average is aligned with the middle month and is descriptive; exponential smoothing produces the requested next-period forecast.`);
addProblem(17,18,`a. The least-squares trend is Tₜ=.928571+1.071429t.\nb. T₉=10.5714 million.`, `The fitted line has slope 45/42=1.071429 and intercept .928571.`);
addProblem(17,19,`The least-squares trend is Tₜ=136+39.181818t, in thousands of cars.\nAt t=11, T₁₁=567 thousand cars.`, `The projection extends the fitted sample trend one period beyond the observed data.`);
addProblem(17,20,`a. Four-quarter moving averages (windows starting at 6-Q1 through 8-Q1): 2.000, 1.875, 1.850, 1.675, 1.750, 1.875, 2.025, 2.200, 2.250. Centered values for t=3…10: 1.9375, 1.8625, 1.7625, 1.7125, 1.8125, 1.9500, 2.1125, 2.2250.\nb. Normalized seasonal factors: Q1=1.152660, Q2=.853435, Q3=1.082281, Q4=.911623.\nc. Removing seasonality from year-6 actuals gives 2.168896, 1.757602, 2.217538, and 1.755111. To seasonalize any year-6 base forecast, multiply its Q1–Q4 values by the four factors above.`, `Part c does not supply a separate base forecast. The answer therefore reports the unambiguous seasonally adjusted observations and states the exact multiplication rule rather than inventing a forecast.`);
addProblem(17,21,`a. Three-day moving-average forecasts: day 4=19, day 5=19, day 6=21, day 7=22.\nb. MSE=(1+81+1+100)/4=45.75.\nc. Mean absolute deviation=(1+9+1+10)/4=5.25.\nd. Forecast for day 7=22.`, `The day-7 forecast uses days 4–6: (18+28+20)/3=22. Its error can be evaluated because the actual day-7 tip is given.`);
addProblem(17,22,`a. With α=.2: F2=105, F3=102, F4=100.6, F5=102.48, F6=102.984.\nb. MSE for weeks 2–6=75.5229.\nc. F7=102.3872.\nd. α=.3 gives MSE=79.3322, so α=.2 is better for these data.`, `Both smoothing constants are compared over the same five forecasted weeks; the smaller MSE determines the better fit.`);
addProblem(17,23,`a. Three-year moving-average forecasts for years 4–11: 24.6667, 25.3333, 24.6667, 23.3333, 22.0000, 23.3333, 23.3333, 26.0000. MSE=7.6667.\nb. With α=.4, forecasts for years 2–11 are 22, 22.8, 24.88, 24.528, 23.5168, 23.71008, 22.226048, 23.735629, 23.841377, 25.504826. MSE=8.4055.\nc. The three-year moving average is better because 7.6667<8.4055.`, `Accuracy is compared on each method's requested forecast range. The moving average has the lower stated MSE.`);
addProblem(17,24,`a. With α=.2: F2=82, F3=81.6, F4=82.08, F5=82.264, F6=81.8112, F7=81.24896.\nb. MSE for days 2–7=4.0332.\nc. F8=81.399168°F.\nd. α=.3 gives MSE=4.3055, so α=.2 is better.`, `The comparison uses identical days for both smoothing constants. The smaller MSE favors α=.2.`);
addProblem(17,25,`The least-squares trend is Tₜ=115.2+9.218182t.\nForecast year 11=216.6000; forecast year 12=225.8182.`, `A linear trend is the appropriate technique because the series shows a persistent upward long-run movement.`);
addProblem(17,26,`a. Four-quarter moving averages: 267.5, 280, 295, 305, 312.5, 327.5, 352.5, 380, 402.5, 422.5, 435, 447.5, 472.5, 485, 505, 525, 532.5. Centered moving averages for t=3…18: 273.75, 287.50, 300.00, 308.75, 320.00, 340.00, 366.25, 391.25, 412.50, 428.75, 441.25, 460.00, 478.75, 495.00, 515.00, 528.75.\nb. Plot interpretation: both series rise; the centered average removes the recurring quarter-to-quarter swings.\nc. Seasonal-irregular ratios for t=3…18: .876712, 1.008696, 1.166667, .971660, .875000, .941176, 1.119454, 1.022364, .945455, .956268, 1.110482, .978261, .919060, 1.030303, 1.048544, 1.002364.\nd. Normalized factors: Q1=1.113202, Q2=.995375, Q3=.905615, Q4=.985807.\ne. Deseasonalized t1…t20: 269.493, 241.115, 265.013, 294.175, 314.408, 301.394, 309.182, 324.607, 368.307, 401.859, 430.647, 415.903, 440.172, 452.091, 485.858, 517.343, 485.087, 532.463, 574.195, 547.774.\nf. Deseasonalized trend: Tₜ=216.300115+17.357531t.\ng. Year-6 forecasts: Q1=646.557, Q2=595.399, Q3=557.427, Q4=623.899 units.`, `The ratio-to-centered-moving-average method is multiplicative. Seasonal ratios are averaged by quarter, normalized to sum to 4, and reapplied after fitting the deseasonalized trend.`);
addProblem(17,27,`a. The least-squares trend is Tₜ=14.385714+.864286t, in thousands.\nb. Forecasts for years 8–12: 21.3000, 22.1643, 23.0286, 23.8929, 24.7571 thousand.`, `The five requested forecasts extend the fitted seven-year linear trend.`);
addProblem(17,28,`a. Four-quarter moving averages: 145, 145, 147.5, 152.5, 155, 160, 162.5, 167.5, 172.5, 180, 182.5, 190, 195. Centered values for t=3…14: 145, 146.25, 150, 153.75, 157.5, 161.25, 165, 170, 176.25, 181.25, 186.25, 192.5.\nb. Seasonal-irregular ratios for t=3…14: 1.103448, 1.025641, 1.000000, .845528, 1.142857, .992248, 1.030303, .823529, 1.134752, .993103, 1.073826, .779221.\nc. Normalized seasonal factors: Q1=1.039521, Q2=.819888, Q3=1.132260, Q4=1.008331.\nd. Deseasonalized t1…t16: 144.297, 146.362, 141.310, 148.761, 144.297, 158.558, 158.974, 158.678, 163.537, 170.755, 176.638, 178.513, 192.396, 182.952, 203.134, 198.348.`, `The factors are normalized to average 1. Deseasonalization divides each actual profit by its quarter's factor.`);
addProblem(17,29,`a. Deseasonalized t1…t16: 16.978, 14.804, 18.727, 6.887, 16.978, 22.206, 26.217, 34.435, 33.956, 29.608, 26.217, 20.661, 33.956, 37.010, 33.708, 48.209.\nb. Fitted deseasonalized trend: Tₜ=11.103664+1.786012t.\nc. Year-5 forecasts: Q1=24.423, Q2=58.433, Q3=60.126, Q4=33.994 crimes.`, `Divide by the supplied factors to remove seasonality, fit the trend to those values, then multiply t=17…20 trend values by the matching quarter factors.`);
addProblem(17,30,`For year 6, t=21…24. Trend values are 92.63, 91.03, 89.43, and 87.83.\nSeasonal forecasts: Q1=111.156; Q2=81.927; Q3=71.544; Q4=96.613.`, `Each trend value is multiplied by its quarter's seasonal factor: 1.2, .9, .8, and 1.1.`);
addProblem(17,31,`a. Four-quarter moving averages: 175, 185, 192.5, 210, 225, 227.5, 235, 242.5, 250. Centered values for t=3…10: 180, 188.75, 201.25, 217.5, 226.25, 231.25, 238.75, 246.25.\nb. Normalized seasonal factors: Q1=.946925, Q2=.980673, Q3=1.114414, Q4=.957988.\nc. Seasonally adjusted year-9 sales: 211.210, 214.139, 233.306, 240.087. To seasonalize a separate year-9 base forecast, multiply its Q1–Q4 entries by the four factors.`, `Part c supplies observed year-9 sales but no separate base forecast. Dividing the observed values gives the unambiguous seasonally adjusted series; the stated factors give the exact rule for any intended forecast.`);

// Chapter 18 problems: signs, rank sums, signed ranks, Kruskal-Wallis
// statistics, and Spearman coefficients were recomputed from the visually
// inspected PDF tables. Exact small-sample probabilities are reported where
// feasible; large-sample rank tests use the normal approximation.
addProblem(18,2,`Exclude 5 indifferent players: n=195.\na. H₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5.\nb. μ=np=97.5.\nc. σ=√[np(1−p)]=√48.75=6.9821.\nd. z=(120−97.5)/6.9821=3.2225; exact two-sided p=.001561. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The preferences differ significantly, with Penn selected more often. Indifferent responses are ties and must be removed before computing n.`);
addProblem(18,3,`a. H₀: the two branch sales distributions are the same; H₁: they differ.\nb. With n₁=n₂=12, μT=12(25)/2=150.\nc. σT=√[12·12·25/12]=17.3205.\nd. z=(184.5−150)/17.3205=1.9919.\ne. Two-sided p≈.0464; reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The given rank sum is just far enough from its null mean to indicate a difference by the large-sample Mann–Whitney–Wilcoxon approximation.`);
addProblem(18,4,`a. H₀: the day and evening score distributions are the same; H₁: they differ.\nb. For n₁=10 and n₂=15, μT=10(26)/2=130.\nc. σT=√[10·15·26/12]=18.0278.\nd. z=(184.5−130)/18.0278=3.0220.\ne. Two-sided p≈.0025; reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The day-student rank sum is much larger than its null expectation, providing evidence that the two score populations differ.`);
addProblem(18,5,`a. The pooled ranks give Branch A rank sum T=148.5.\nb. μT=150.\nc. σT≈17.3205 (17.3167 with the tie correction for the two values of 250).\nd. z≈−.0866, two-sided p≈.931. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The observed rank sum is almost exactly its null mean, so the samples do not show a significant difference between branch sales distributions.`);
addProblem(18,6,`a. The day-student rank sum is T=74.5.\nb. μT=10(21)/2=105.\nc. σT=√[10·10·21/12]=13.2288 (13.2238 with the tie correction for age 30).\nd. z≈−2.306, two-sided p≈.0211. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `Day students occupy substantially lower pooled age ranks, so the two age distributions differ significantly.`);
addProblem(18,7,`H₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5, where p is the probability that the wife initiates filing.\nn=60, x=41, μ=30, σ=√15=3.8730, z=2.8402. Exact two-sided p=.006218. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The filing initiator is not evenly split between wives and husbands in these cases; wives initiated more often.`);
addProblem(18,9,`After excluding the zero difference, signed ranks for After−Before give W+=11 and W−=4 (n=5).\nFor H₁: median improvement>0, the exact one-sided p=.25. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The large gain of 16 receives the highest rank, but two negative differences and the very small effective sample prevent a significant conclusion that the seminar is effective.`);
addProblem(18,10,`There are 12 plus signs and 3 minus signs.\nH₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5. Exact two-sided p=2P[Bin(15,.5)≤3]=.035156. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `Imported cars are preferred significantly more often in this sample because “+” denotes imported.`);
addProblem(18,11,`There are 14 plus signs and 6 minus signs.\nH₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5. Exact two-sided p=2P[Bin(20,.5)≤6]=.115318. Do not reject H₀.`, `Although the Democratic candidate has more plus signs, the difference is not statistically significant at α=.05.`);
addProblem(18,12,`Exclude 10 ties: n=110, with 60 foreign and 50 domestic preferences.\nH₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5. μ=55, σ=√27.5=5.2440, z=.9535; exact two-sided p=.39093. Do not reject H₀.`, `The ten-response difference is small relative to the sign-test sampling variation once ties are removed.`);
addProblem(18,13,`Exclude 20 indifferent shoppers: n=280, with 160 fluoride and 120 nonfluoride preferences.\nH₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5. μ=140, σ=√70=8.3666, z=2.3905; exact two-sided p=.019607. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The sign test detects a significant preference difference, favoring fluoride toothpaste.`);
addProblem(18,14,`Using After−Before and excluding the zero difference, W+=36.5 and W−=8.5 for n=9.\nFor H₁: median improvement>0, exact one-sided p=.05469. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The result is very close but does not meet the 5% level under the exact signed-rank test, so effectiveness is not established.`);
addProblem(18,15,`All ten paired differences A−B are positive, so W+=55 and W−=0.\nExact two-sided p=2/2¹⁰=.001953. Reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `Model A travels farther for every driver in the sample, providing strong evidence that the two models differ; the observed direction favors Model A.`);
addProblem(18,16,`Exclude 6 no-change responses: n=15, with 11 reporting less and 4 more violence.\nH₀:p=.5; H₁:p>.5 for “less violence.” Exact one-sided p=P[Bin(15,.5)≥11]=.059235. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The result narrowly misses 5%, so the survey does not provide sufficient evidence that the letters reduced violence.`);
addProblem(18,17,`Using New−Old and excluding two zero differences gives n=13, W+=53.5 and W−=37.5.\nFor H₁: median increase>0, exact one-sided p≈.29993. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `Positive and negative production changes are mixed; the signed ranks do not establish that the new machines increased production.`);
addProblem(18,18,`Exclude 49 no-change employees: n=51, with 36 smoking less and 15 more.\na. H₀:p=.5; H₁:p≠.5 (the campaign has an influence).\nb. μ=25.5, σ=√12.75=3.5707, z=2.9406; exact two-sided p=.004601. Reject H₀ at α=.01.`, `The campaign is associated with a significant directional change, and the larger group reports smoking less.`);
VERIFIED_ANSWERS['ch18-problem-019']={status:'source-error',confidence:'high',answer:'Cannot be uniquely tested from the printed data.',explanation:'The source says n=80, but its categories contain 30 under 21, 45 over 21, and 10 equal to 21—a total of 85. The sign-test sample size after removing ties is therefore ambiguous (70 if n=80, but 75 from the printed category counts). No answer is guessed.'};
addProblem(18,20,`a. H₀: the day- and night-shift productivity distributions are the same; H₁: they differ.\nb. Pooled day-shift rank sum T=111.0; μT=110; σT≈14.2009 (14.1917 with tie correction). z≈.0705, two-sided p≈.944. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The day-shift rank sum is nearly identical to its null expectation; productivity distributions are not significantly different.`);
addProblem(18,21,`a. H₀: the three age-group sales distributions are the same; H₁: at least one differs.\nb. Rank sums are 40, 69, and 101. Tie-corrected Kruskal–Wallis H=5.6970, df=2, p=.05793; χ².05,2=5.991. Do not reject H₀.`, `The over-45 group has the largest ranks, but the overall difference narrowly misses the 5% significance threshold.`);
addProblem(18,22,`Σd²=38, so rₛ=1−6(38)/[12(12²−1)]=.867133.\nUsing t=rₛ√[(n−2)/(1−rₛ²)]=5.5054 with df=10 gives two-sided p≈.000260. Reject H₀ at α=.02.`, `The two faculty rankings have a strong, statistically significant positive association.`);
addProblem(18,23,`Rank sums: Accounting=38, Management=56, Marketing=42.\nTie-corrected Kruskal–Wallis H=.36795, df=2, p=.83196. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The rank distributions are very similar, providing no evidence that performance differs among the three majors.`);
addProblem(18,24,`Σd²=294, so rₛ=−.027972. The t approximation is −.08849 with df=10, p≈.9312. Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The correlation is essentially zero; the female and male student rankings do not show statistically significant agreement.`);
addProblem(18,25,`Σd²=78, so rₛ=.071429. For n=8, t=.17541 with df=6, p≈.8665 (exact two-sided p≈.8820). Do not reject H₀.`, `The two automobile rankings have almost no positive association and are not significantly correlated.`);
addProblem(18,26,`Σd²=30, so rₛ=.642857. For n=8, t=2.0557 with df=6, p≈.0856 (exact two-sided p≈.0962). Do not reject H₀ at α=.05.`, `The sample association is moderately positive, but eight activities do not provide enough evidence for significance at 5%.`);
addProblem(18,27,`Σd²=24, so rₛ=−.20. For n=5, t=−.3536 with df=3, p≈.7471 (exact two-sided p≈.7833). Do not reject H₀.`, `The rankings have a weak negative sample association that is not statistically significant.`);
addProblem(18,28,`Rank sums: Northern=37.5, Central=43.0, Southern=39.5.\nTie-corrected Kruskal–Wallis H=.15528, df=2, p=.92530; χ².01,2=9.210. Do not reject H₀.`, `The three university score distributions are extremely similar in rank terms; there is no significant difference at α=.01.`);
